    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-04-24T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-04-24T03:00:00-05:00" n="504"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d504">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20200(D)/4–2446: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-24T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 24, 1946—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 24—8:39 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1312. For Benton from Smith. Lozovski informed me by letter dated April 23 that
                    Central Organization for Delivery of Newspapers and Magazines throughout USSR
                        (<gloss target="#t_Soyuzpechat1">Soyuzpechat</gloss>) will undertake
                    distribution of 50,000 copies of illustrated magazine <hi rend="italic"
                        >America</hi> beginning June 1 this year. Hope this news, which means <hi
                        rend="italic">America</hi> can operate without loss, will persuade Congress
                    to permit continuance of magazine.<note n="88" xml:id="d504fn88">A Department of
                        State press release of August 30, 1946, announced the permission for this
                        increase in circulation at 10 rubles a copy; Department of State <hi
                            rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, September 15, 1946, pp. 513–514. The
                        Committee on Appropriations of the House of Representatives had temporarily
                        favored discontinuance of the magazine because of its limited distribution
                        and cost of publication.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
